6036 Peninsula Robotics is proud to show off PeninsulaPortal, a toolkit of robot diagnosis and debugging tools, path planning tools, and a more!

This app is currently in it’s development phase. So, we have no binaries available! Check out our repository for usage notes and contributions! If there are any issues, feel free to submit them on Github!

Github Repository

Lets show off some of our subfeatures!

WPILOG, CSV, and NT4 support

Dynamic UI with resizable paneled view

Drag-and-drop navigation

Convenient log field search

Graph view window, color selection, and expression mapping

The ability to “hook” certain boolean topics to certain parameters

Fully supported odometry system Works with AdvantageScope’s Mechanism Color selection, transparency toggles 2D: pose trails, display type selection 3D: camera controls, individual model selection

Works with AdvantageScope’s Mechanism

3D: camera controls, individual model selection

Video downloading and syncing

Project / layout saving, with multiple projects allowed

Field configuration

Drag-and-drop waypoints and obstacles

Multi-waypoint selection and editing

Multi-path creation and editing

Custom coloring and display styles

Python path generation script support

Each waypoint can have custom JSON key-values

Custom JSON key-values for entire path generation

Project saving, with multiple projects allowed

The default generator script is currently a WIP! We’ll get back to you when Ashray is finished!

Usage of PeninsulaPortal’s odometry visuals within custom Python driverstation dashboards

Application appearance selection

Custom template / field creation and configuration for each year’s game

Custom robot model creation, with component configuration through UI alone

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
It’s cool to see all the ongoing innovation in tools built on top of NT4 and DataLog!  We welcome feedback on any issues you’ve run into with interfacing to WPILib components for these aspects.

What drove the choice of straight JavaScript over using TypeScript?

I am slightly concerned about the use of random IDs in the NT4 implementation–while the probability of a collision may be low, it’s not zero (and I prefer zero).

It was pretty good for us this season especially with being able to quickly modify and add constraints easily throughout robot development since it’s python and the flexibility of the json fields in the editor. (I heavily encourage members of the open source community to rewrite or upgrade this since it’s somewhat messy from the season and can probably have more features too) (also maybe sleipnir?)

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked:
How well did the solver itself do? What kind of formulation and constraints did you use, how robust was it, and how long did it take to solve?

I’ve noticed that for direct transcription problems with a variable dt, CasADi + Ipopt likes to randomly report infeasible and can take a long time to solve.

posts.name: Jeffrey
posts.cooked:
Peter_Johnson:

What drove the choice of straight JavaScript over using TypeScript?

There was no huge reason, and when this project started about a year ago, JavaScript was all that I was familiar with. I do kind of regret not using TypeScript then…

Peter_Johnson:

I am slightly concerned about the use of random IDs in the NT4 implementation–while the probability of a collision may be low, it’s not zero (and I prefer zero).

That is a valid concern. I’ll look into how we can avoid this issue. I will note that AdvantageScope does the exact same in their implementation, and all other implementations seem to do something similar.

It’s between a 5 to 40 second solve usually but yeah I don’t love casadi + ipopt and wish I had time to try sleipnir or something else for it (truth be told I wrote this last summer while learning nlp). Infeasible reports were rare enough but the good old “move it a little” fixed that. One of the bigger reasons I hope people will evolve this.

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: Wouldn’t be too hard to try Sleipnir; it’s a similar API to CasADi, but with a way faster solver. Robustness is my primary concern with it though, which is why Choreo still hasn’t completely dropped its CasADi backend. Part of the problem is the formulation itself being poorly behaved, but interior-point methods in general seem to struggle with minimum-time trajectory optimization.

Yeah I hope due to the app independence and being able to write in python, people will be able to rapidly develop and test new solutions in the future and contribute. There’s a ton of promising methodologies in research everywhere.

posts.name: Ezra
posts.cooked: It looks great! When do you plan on releasing it?

posts.name: Jeffrey
posts.cooked: The code is currently released, but due to maintainability it might be refactored soon so that everything is more readable. An official binary release is still some ways away but we’re working on it.
